{"title_page": "Stumpery", "text_new": "[[File:Stumpery.jpg|thumb|250px|A stumpery under construction for the [[Hampton Court Flower Show]]]]\n\nA '''stumpery''' is a [[garden feature]] similar to a [[rockery]] but made from parts of dead trees.  This can take the form of whole stumps, logs, pieces of bark or even worked timber such as railway sleepers or floorboards.  The pieces are arranged artistically and plants, typically [[fern]]s, [[moss]]es and [[lichen]]s are encouraged to grow around or on them.  They provide a feature for the garden and a habitat for several types of wildlife.  The first stumpery was built in 1856 at [[Biddulph Grange]] and they remained popular in [[Victorian Britain]].\n\nA stumpery traditionally consists of tree stumps arranged upside-down or on their sides to show the root structure but logs, driftwood or large pieces of bark can also be used.<ref name=\"courier\"/>  The stumps can be used individually or attached together to form a structure such as a wall or arch.  Stumperies can vary in size from a handful of logs to large displays containing dozens of full tree stumps.<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{Citation  | last =  Klein| first = Carol  | title = Turn your eyesore into an asset  | newspaper = Daily Telegraph  | pages =   | date =  20 November 2003 | url =https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/gardenprojects/3315728/Turn-your-eyesore-into-an-asset.html }}</ref>  The use of storm-damaged or diseased trees is not uncommon and can save the landowner the cost of their removal.<ref name=\"courier\"/><ref name=\"penn\">{{Citation  | last =  Layton| first = Karen| title = Stumped? Turn an eyesore into a garden asset| pages =   | year = | date =  | url =http://monroe.extension.psu.edu/Horticulture/gardenspot/Stumps_and_Stumperies.pdf| accessdate = 2009-02-01}}</ref>  Where tree stumps are unavailable a more modern, angular look can be achieved by using railway sleepers or old oak floorboards and some companies sell waste timber or driftwood specifically for the purpose of constructing stumperies.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>  Plants such as ferns, mosses and lichens are often encouraged to grow around and on the stumpery.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>  Stumperies provide a home for wildlife and have been known to host [[stag beetle]]s, [[toad]]s and small mammals.<ref name=\"wild\"/><ref name=\"guardian\">{{Citation  | last =  Sturgeon | first = Andy | title =Anatomy of a garden: Highgrove Stumpery| newspaper = The Guardian  | pages =   | date =  16 December 2006 | url =https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2006/dec/16/gardens1}}</ref>\n\n[[File:France Loir-et-Cher Festival jardins Chaumont-sur-Loire 2005 13 Stumpery 01.jpg|thumb|left|Part of the stumpery at the [[Ch\u00e2teau de Chaumont]], central France]]\nStumperies have been described as \"Victorian horticultural oddities\" and were popular features of 19th-century gardens.<ref name=\"wild\">{{Citation  | last =  The Wildlife Trusts | first =  | author-link =  The Wildlife Trusts | last2 = Royal Horticultural Society  | first2 =   | author2-link =  Royal Horticultural Society  | title =  Cheshire garden wins silver! | date =   | year =   | url = http://www.wildaboutgardens.org/News/Story.aspx?ses=8BRNdOh280y1fEhV4T7kng%3D%3D&topicspage=0&TopicID=XUrHjWz2r0yBeS6phZclaA%3D%3D  | accessdate = 2009-02-01 }}</ref>  The reasons for their popularity vary but it may be a result of the [[Romantic Movement]] which emphasised the beauty of nature.<ref name=\"seattle\">{{Citation  | last =  Easton| first = Valorie| title = In this island woodland, stumped is not a bad thing| newspaper = Seattle Times  | pages =   | date =  25 May 2008 | url =http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/pacificnw/2004431631_pacificplife25.html?syndication=rss}}</ref>  Their popularity may also be attributed to the increasing [[Pteridomania|popularity of fern]]s as garden plants at the time.  Ferns were very fashionable and hundreds of new species were introduced to Britain from around the world.  The stumpery made an ideal habitat for these shade-loving plants.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>  Additionally stumperies may have been used in place of [[rockery|rockeries]] in areas where suitable rocks were in short supply.<ref name=\"news\">{{Citation  | last =  Hughes| first = Roger| title = Fern Garden Stumpery| newspaper = Stephen F. Austin State University: Arboretum News  | pages =   | date =  Autumn 2003 | url =http://ag.sfasu.edu/UserFiles/File/ArbNewsletters/2003%20Fall.pdf}}</ref>  Their popularity is once again on the rise.<ref name=\"penn\"/>\n\nThe first stumpery to be built, at [[Biddulph Grange]], [[Staffordshire]], in 1856, was designed by the artist and gardener [[Edward William Cooke]] for the estate's owner [[James Bateman]].<ref name=\"courier\">{{Citation  | last =  Mallory | first = Julie  | title = Stumpery makes good use of storm debris  | newspaper = Evansville Courier & Press  | pages =   | date =  1 June 2007  | url =http://www.courierpress.com/news/2007/jun/01/stumpery-makes-good-use-of-storm-debris/ }}</ref>  The stumpery at Biddulph Grange consists of stumps placed into a {{convert|10|ft|m}} wall either side of a garden path and used as a scaffold for the growth of ferns.<ref name=\"courier\"/><ref name=\"seattle\"/>  A famous modern stumpery is that at [[Highgrove House]], [[Gloucestershire]], the home of [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles]], which is considered to be the largest stumpery in Britain.<ref name=\"country\">{{Citation|last=Russell |first=Tony |title=The Gardens at Highgrove |newspaper=Country Gardener |url=http://www.countrygardener.co.uk/features/biggarden/gardensathighgrove.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208143916/http://countrygardener.co.uk/features/biggarden/gardensathighgrove.html |archivedate=8 February 2009 }}</ref>  The Prince built the stumpery from [[sweet chestnut]] roots, held in place by steel bars, when he first purchased the estate in 1980, and it now provides a home for organically grown ferns, [[hellebore]]s and [[hosta]]s.<ref name=\"guardian\"/><ref name=\"news\"/>  The largest stumpery in the [[United States]] is at [[Vashon Island]] in [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]].<ref name=\"seattle\"/>  It rivals the Highgrove stumpery in size, measuring {{convert|9000|sqft|m2}} and including around 95 separate tree stumps.<ref name=\"seattle\"/>  Stumperies can sometimes be mistaken for garden rubbish; indeed, when [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip]] first saw his son's stumpery, he remarked: \"When are you going to set fire to this lot?\".<ref name=\"guardian\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Garden features}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Garden features]]\n[[Category:Horticulture and gardening]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Stumpery.jpg|thumb|250px|A stumpery under construction for the [[Hampton Court Flower Show]]]]\n\nA '''stumpery''' is a [[garden feature]] similar to a [[rockery]] but made from parts of dead trees.  This can take the form of whole stumps, logs, pieces of bark or even worked timber such as railway sleepers or floorboards.  The pieces are arranged artistically and plants, typically [[fern]]s, [[moss]]es and [[lichen]]s are encouraged to grow around or on them.  They provide a feature for the garden and a habitat for several types of wildlife.  The first stumpery was built in 1856 at [[Biddulph Grange]] and they remained popular in [[Victorian Britain]].\n\nA stumpery traditionally consists of tree stumps arranged upside-down or on their sides to show the root structure but logs, driftwood or large pieces of bark can also be used.<ref name=\"courier\"/>  The stumps can be used individually or attached together to form a structure such as a wall or arch.  Stumperies can vary in size from a handful of logs to large displays containing dozens of full tree stumps.<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{Citation  | last =  Klein| first = Carol  | title = T